<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18470301-842">
               <interp inst="t18470301-842" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18470301"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18470301-842" type="date" value="18470301"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470301-842-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-842-18470301 t18470301-842-offence-1 t18470301-842-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>842. <persName id="def1-842-18470301" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-842-18470301" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-842-18470301" type="age" value="18"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-842-18470301" type="surname" value="SPRINGFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-842-18470301" type="given" value="CHARLOTTE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">CHARLOTTE SPRINGFIELD</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18470301-842-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470301-842-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470301-842-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp>for a like offence.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. CLARKE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">LAW</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">ELIZABETH PERCY</hi>. I am the daughter of James Percy, a dairyman, in Friar-street, Lambeth. On Thursday night, the 14th of Jan., about nine o'clock, the prisoner came for a pint of milk, and gave me a bad half-crown—I gave it to my brother, who bent it and returned it to me—he told the prisoner it was a bad one, and he would keep it—she said, "If the young man intends to keep it, I will go and fetch my husband"—she went out—my brother followed her—I laid the half-crown on the mantel-piece—we kept it in the shop till the officer came, and I showed it him—sergeant Goff took it off the counter—I am quite sure he took the same half-crown the prisoner gave me—I saw him take it from the counter—that was a week afterwards—it had remained on the shelf about a week—no one was there but me—I then desired my brother to nail it and another piece of bad money on the counter—I know it to be the one the prisoner gave me by the teeth-marks next to the crown—the same marks were on it when it was put on the shelf—my brother had marked it with his teeth.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1114" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1114" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1114" type="surname" value="PERCY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1114" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD PERCY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the brother of Elizabeth Percy. I recollect her receiving this half-crown—I placed it between my teeth, and bent it—the prisoner was in the shop, standing at the door—I said, "I shall keep this"—she said, "If the young man is going to keep it, I shall fetch my husband"—she left the shop—I gave the half-crown to my sister, and followed the prisoner some distance—I then lost sight of her—I saw the half-crown again when I went back, on the mantel-shelf behind the counter—it remained there nearly a week—I saw it on the shelf during the week—my brother then nailed it on the counter—I can say it was the same, by my teeth marks and by the way I bent it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> When I was taken up you could not say whether it was me or not. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I swear to her by her face.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1115" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1115" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1115" type="surname" value="PERCY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1115" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES PERCY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the brother of Richard Percy. I saw a bad half-crown in my father's shop—I nailed it on the counter about a fortnight after the prisoner brought it in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1116" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1116" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1116" type="surname" value="GOFF"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1116" type="given" value="CHARLES BURGESS"></interp>CHARLES BURGESS GOFF</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant L</hi> 8.) On Friday, the 29th of Jan., I went to Mr. Percy's house, and saw a half-crown nailed to the counter—I took it away—Elizabeth Percy was present—I produce the half-crown.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1117" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1117" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1117" type="surname" value="HOSKINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1117" type="given" value="ALICE"></interp>ALICE HOSKINS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of John Hoskins; we live in Vauxhall-road. On the 17th of Jan. the prisoner came for a pint of milk, which came to 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—she gave me a half-crown—I felt it was smooth on the head side—I looked at her—(I knew she had passed a bad 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. piece to me last summer)—I told her I had I had not got change—I went down to Mr. Hawkins's shop, and showed the half-crown to her—I came back to my house and I said to the prisoner, "I shall not give you this money, nor the mug; you well knew this was a bad one"—she said she did not; she would go and fetch her husband—she went out—I followed but lost her in Francis-street—I put the half-crown on</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184703010178"></xptr>
               <p>a table, under a mug—the policeman came the next day, and told me to take care of it—I marked it, put it into a bit of paper, and marked it with the day of the month and the year—I put it into a drawer, where it remained till the 1st of Feb., when I gave it to the officer Stickley.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> If you were aware it was bad, why did you want to go to a shop to get change? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> To have a witness that it was bad.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1118" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1118" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1118" type="surname" value="STICKLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1118" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD STICKLEY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable L</hi> 79.) On the 18th of Jan. I went to Mr. Hoskins's house—she produced a half-crown, and marked it in my presence—I did not take it away then—on the 1st of Feb. she gave me the same half-crown—it was in the same paper, and marked with the day of the month.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1119" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1119" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1119" type="surname" value="URSELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1119" type="given" value="LOUISA"></interp>LOUISA URSELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of John Ursell; I assist in the shop of Mr. Elliot. On the 28th of Jan., about nine o'clolck in the evening, the pri<lb></lb>soner came for an ounce of 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. tea, and half a pound of sugar—they came to 7<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—she put a crown-piece on the counter—I took it up, and found it was bad—I handed it to Mr. Elliott, who was standing by my side—he asked the prisoner where she lived—she said, "At No. 9, in this street," pointing to some street—he asked where she got it—she said her husband had given it her, and she would fetch him, and went out—I said I would not let it pass off, and Mr. Elliott went with her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did you not drop it into the till, and then pick it up and say, "I don't think this is a good one?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I put it into no till at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1120" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1120" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1120" type="surname" value="ELLIOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1120" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES ELLIOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep a shop at No. 14, Barrett-street, Lambeth. On the evening of the 28th of Jan. I saw the prisoner between eight and nine o'clock—she was served by Louisa Ursell, who handed a crown-piece to me, and said she did not think it was good—I had seen the prisoner give it her—I looked at it, and asked the prisoner where she got it—she said her hus<lb></lb>band gave it her—I asked where she lived—she said, "At No. 9, down Little Park-street"—I went with her—she led me down a street or two, and then I met an officer, who took her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> She dropped it in the till? <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> No, on my oath she did not—the till was not open.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1121" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1121" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1121" type="surname" value="PIPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1121" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES PIPER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable L</hi> 76) On the 28th of Jan. I met the prisoner and Mr. Elliott in New-street—I took the prisoner—I asked her where she lived—she said, anywhere, where she could get money.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1122" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1122" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1122" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1122" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>MR. JOHN FIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am inspector of coin to the Royal Mint—these half-crowns are both counterfeit, and I believe have been cast in the same mould—this crown-piece is also counterfeit in all respects.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I did not know it was bad; I am an unfortunate girl; I said my husband gave it me, not being aware what it was; the two half-crowns I know nothing at all about.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
